text: OH.MY.GOD I am officially dead. This is AMAZING  ! I'm going to Spoil and Fangirl, read at your own risks.     SPOIL : 00:14 The Greenhouse, with the snow it's just perfect. 00:19 Here it is ! 00:27 District 2 ! 00:32 KILL ME, IT'S THE EPILOGUE OR NEAR THE END ! 00:35 The Meadow... 01:17 Here come the tears. 01:30 My baby is speaking :,) 01:41 IS THAT WHAT I THINK ? " And that's when the rest of the parachutes go off" 01:42 I thought there was no water in the sewers.. 01:41 ...NOOOOOO 01:51 Are they heartless ? 01:57 Last time you see day light ! 02:03 DON'T TOUCH THAT !! 02:05 You see that hovercraft in the background ? We all know who's inside... 02:06 Meat grinder. 02:13 Johanna :D 02:14 They are really disturbing and disgusting..  Katnisssss... 02:15 Tigris (she's creepy) 02:15 !!!!!!!! Evellark, enven if it's not real  So, so, so. I CRIED SO HARD. This trailer is amazing, despite  some negative points like the huge spoil of the parachute scene, I mean, they showed an explosion with Katniss on a truck, then they show people with parachute while Katniss is on the truck, then they show the children trying to catch 'em. Are they serious ? The mutts..wasn't it supposed to be a surprise ? I mean they showed half of the scene... Katniss doesn't look much damaged. And she is not supposed to be so close to the barricade, and here she's just in front of it ! And the entire teaser trailer is in this one I mean one or two scenes is okay, but the entire teaser ?  In conclusion, I love this trailer, it's amazing and marvelous and all, but there is too much spoil for me. They show too much Capitol scenes, so Evellark shouldn't be in the trailer, neither the mutts and the parachutes.   But there are a lot of good stuff though, like Tigris, I couldn't picture her well in the book but here she's very good. The lizzards, that I couldn't imagine at all are also reallt good (a little too human but really good). Snow is perfect as usual and the warfare looks good.  I have huge expectations for this movie, I hope the PG13 won't ruin it, I hope I won't be disappointed.

text: No point in watching the movie because I have it summarized below:  Katniss, her sister Prim, and her friends Finnick and Gale all reluctantly adjust to a highly structured life in the underground District 13, which has been spearheading the rebellion in Panem. Feeling manipulated, Katniss eventually agrees to act as "the Mockingjay"—a poster child for the rebellion—but only on the condition that District 13's President Alma Coin vows to grant immunity to all of the past Hunger Games tributes, including Katniss's friend Peeta Mellark and Finnick's lover Annie Cresta, and to reserve for Katniss the right to personally kill Panem's President Snow once he is captured.  Katniss and the rebels learn that Peeta is alive and is being tortured at the Capitol in an attempt to demoralize and control Katniss. When a rescue team succeeds in extracting him, they discover that Peeta has been "hijacked"—a brutal form of brainwashing involving the use of Tracker Jacker venom that induces extreme fear. Peeta has been programmed to hate and fear Katniss. After he attempts to kill her, he is kept restrained under heavy guard at all times as the rebel medics seek a way to restore him to sanity.  A controversial strategy proposed by Gale wins a decisive victory at District 2, readying the rebels to launch a final campaign against the Capitol itself. Katniss and her propo team (a film crew recording her squad for rebel propaganda) are deployed on a trivial assignment to the Capitol. President Coin has sent Peeta along on the mission even though he is still dangerous and unpredictable. Katniss believes Coin wants her dead because she is difficult to control.  While filming in a purportedly safe Capitol neighborhood, the team's commander, Boggs, is killed. Subsequently, during intense urban warfare that involves Hunger Games-like monsters, most of Katniss' team mates, including Finnick, are killed. Katniss presses on alone towards President Snow's mansion. As Katniss reaches the mansion, a hoverplane drops parachutes carrying bombs that explode among a group of trapped children. The rebel medics (including Katniss' sister Prim) rush in to help the injured children but in a deliberately inhumane strategy, a second wave of firebombs explodes, taking out the medics. Prim is killed and Katniss sustains severe burns, but the rebels succeed in taking the Capitol.  During her recuperation, Katniss becomes deeply depressed over her sister's death and confronts prisoner Snow. Snow claims that Coin orchestrated the bombing that resulted in Prim's death, persuasively arguing that Coin made it appear to be Snow's work in order to turn his supporters against him. Katniss realizes in horror that the strategy used to kill the medics had been developed earlier by Gale. When Katniss confronts Gale about his possible involvement, he merely expresses uncertainty. Katniss becomes convinced that rather than establishing a republic governed by representatives from each of the districts, Coin intends to assume Snow's power and maintain the status quo.  On the day Snow is to be executed, President Coin asks the remaining Hunger Games victors to vote on punishing the Capitol just as the Capitol punished the Districts: by holding a final Hunger Games that will target the children of the Capitol's leaders. Katniss silently reflects that this is exactly the same evil the Capitol committed when the last rebellion failed. Then, she votes "yes—for Prim." Haymitch is the only one who understands her hidden meaning. They proceed to the execution, where Katniss is to shoot Snow. As she readies her bow, Snow flashes her one last smile, reminding her of his promise to always be truthful to her. Katniss silently agrees and, making her decision, she raises her bow and shoots Coin instead, killing her. Katniss immediately attempts suicide, but Peeta stops her and she is arrested during the ensuing riot. After the riot, Snow is found dead. Katniss is ultimately acquitted of Coin's murder by reason of insanity, and she is relocated to the ruins of her home in District 12.  Months later, Peeta and some other District 12 natives also return there. Peeta has gradually recovered the memories of his love for Katniss. Katniss embraces her love for Peeta, recognizing her need for his hope and strength. Together, they write a book in order to preserve the memory of those who died. Peeta still suffers flashbacks from his hijacking and Katniss still wakes up screaming from nightmares. By helping overthrow Snow and assassinating Coin, Katniss has preserved the possibility of Panem transitioning to a representative form of government, but at a tremendous personal cost.  In the epilogue set 20 years later, Katniss and Peeta have two children. The Hunger Games are over for good, and the children represent hope that future generations will benefit from the sacrifices of their parents. Katniss dreads the day her children learn about their parents' involvement in both the Games and the war. When she feels distressed, Katniss plays a comforting but repetitive game: reminding herself of every good thing she has ever seen someone do. The series ends with Katniss' somber reflection that "There are much worse games to play

text: I caught an interview with Donald Sutherland where he was interviewed about these films. And the woman interviewing him asked something like: "what advice would you give to people wanting to start a revolution?" And instead of saying: "look, i'm just an actor, and these are just movies" he unthinkingly just repeated an idea from the film and said: "find a leader".  And it got me thinking, apart from the fact that 90% of hollywood actors seem to be nasty dumb socialists, these movies really have a horrible political message.  They're an insight into the fantasies of social democrats and how these people see themselves as rebels, when in actual fact you can tell they idolatries the state, and violence, and are motivated mainly by a confused resentment.   These films seem to me like a cross between Mein Kampf and a juvenile John Green romance. It's like a Hitler or Mussolini big man syndrome mixed with an immature girls fantasy about a love triangle.

text: The problem with this trailer is that is touts Snow as the quintessential "bad guy." But the the thing I liked most about the Hunger Games is that there isn't really a "bad guy" that must be defeated in order for peace to be restored. The "real enemy" is the system--the whole organization of their government. Snow did not create the concept of the districts nor did he create the games. He needs to be dethroned in order for a new government to be installed, but he is not the root of all the problems in Panem, is more complicated than that.

text: I read the books years ago, and have always wanted them to be released as films. I watched the first 5 seconds of the Hunger Games trailer and knew exactly what it was. Nobody else had a fucking clue. And now everybody's jumped on the Hunger Games bandwagon saying the movies are amazing! They aren't nearly as good as the books! The Hunger Games trilogy in my opinion should have been an 18 rating for ALL films but because they weren't they are ridiculously tame. In the books, it is terrifying what Katniss has to go through, but in the movies it looks like nothing! To me, this film should be amazing as it represents the best part of Mockingjay, but I have a feeling it may disappoint me as it won't come close to the detail in the book :(

text: I read the Hunger Games when I was in fifth grade. Everybody in my class was reading it because the first movie was coming out soon. Finally I got the first book, and it was my first actual book. What I mean about this is I was never a reader before this trilogy, at the time I barely knew what a trilogy was. I finished the first book and watched the movie in a fork and screen movie theater and was a bit scared of the mutated dogs. and then finished the next two during the summer and I finished it both books in four weeks (I was also in summer camp) and from there I kept up with the news and trailers and for both catching fire and mockingjay pt 1 i was first in line rereading the book the first day, and first showing that the movie came out. The hunger games has helped become who I am as a reader and helped developed my personality (I am a complete fangirl and nerd). So thank you Suzzane Collins and I will probably cry when this last movie comes out.

No prob, we simply execute you now, because: that's the whole point of the Hunger Games, that we CAN do anything we want, even choosing two teens out of each district and letting them fight each other to the death and you still won't do anything at all about it."  Later the Capitol had many more simply chances to kill Katniss without a problem. Or capture and drug her into a zombie following their lead. Or just use their ultra technique and generate videos of her doing anything they want, for example slaughtering children of the Capitol or eating poop or whatever.  Instead they ruin their own city with ridiculous traps. o_O  Come one, you could at least TRY to put some sense in it. I mean, you copied battle royal anyway and this made much more sense, putting misbehaving teens into a sick fight to the death, so that all others will behave and try to be good to not end like this. text: Mis cómplices, no se pierdan este film!!.  La taquillera franquicia de Hunger Games ha tenido un éxito arrasador con el público de todo el mundo y ha recaudado más de 2200 millones de dólares a nivel internacional. The Hunger Games: Mockingjay - Part 2 llevará ahora a la franquicia a su poderoso capítulo final en el que Katniss Everdeen [Jennifer Lawrence] se da cuenta de que lo que está en juego ya no son sólo sus vidas, sino el futuro.  La nación de Panem está sumida en una guerra sin cuartel y Katniss confronta al presidente Snow [Donald Sutherland] en el enfrentamiento final. Junto a un equipo compuesto por sus amigos más cercanos, entre los que se encuentran Gale [Liam Hemsworth], Finnick [Sam Claflin] y Peeta [Josh Hutcherson], Katniss emprende una misión con la unidad del Distrito 13 mientras arriesgan sus vidas para liberar a los ciudadanos de Panem, organizando un intento de asesinato del presidente Snow, quién está cada vez más obsesionado con destruirla. Las trampas letales, los enemigos y las decisiones morales que le esperan a Katniss la desafiarán incluso más que cualquier situación que haya enfrentado en The Hunger Games.  Que la disfruten, mis cómplices!!!.  Un beso enorme  AC

text: Just saw hunger games Mockingjay part two. Honestly it was a good movie but your chain somethings from the book. In the first part I thought it was kind of boring because for me I like to see action action action but that was OK. So I thought Gail was being kind of selfish. I think deep down inside he knew that Katniss didn't really love him the way she loves Peter but he wanted to make himself believe that. There were moments when he was trying to get Katniss away from pita and also he was giving her weird looks when ever she had moments with him. At first cat miss and pita slow was just a spectacle for the capital for the hunger games but it soon turned out to be real feelings for him and I'm happy that Katniss chose the person who She truthfully loved in the end. Next, President CO I N. I knew she was power crazed from the start. I mean think about it. Why was she so eager to go into the capital and aluminate President snow? Because she wanted to take his place, Like President snow said. And when she made that plan with everyone to take the capital children and do a revenge hunger games with them? I'm not gonna lie. I want to see how that turned out, but when you think rationally, The reason why she was killed in the end is because if she really did do that hunger games with the capital children the wars would still continue and President snow dying would do absolutely nothing. That is why ultimately, Katniss had to shoot an arrow through her heart. It was just going to keep going in circles and everyone would just have to keep killing for president snowexactly what he wanted. Now the matter of Finnick dying: 😩. When finished died I'm knocking ally I almost cried. He was a good character, But since this was the series finale movie, the good characters always die. All I was thinking is that Annie and her baby would be alone. Next, the matter of prim dying: it's not that I didn't care but haven't you noticed that in all of the series the young people never make it to the end? And people were saying that Katniss had no emotion when she died, but I know Katniss was sad on the inside but she was too invested in everything that was going on. She didn't really have time to grieve. She had to finish the rebellion once and for all and then grieve afterwards. Now the matter of President Snow: he truthfully is a monster inside and out. One of his general said that Katniss would die from her own arrogance, but in the end it was President snow that die from his own arrogance, and he was also sick with those disgusting cold sores in his mouth. So in the end he died while coughing up his own blood, and the people attacked him. Well, so much people died in the end and there was so much emotions and so many things going on but in the end, the true end, everything was happy. Pita and Katniss finally headpiece for once in a very long time. The movie never showed what happened to Gail in the end but I'm guessing by the telling of what people said about him, He married and important person's daughter and I guess he was happy. And cat miss and pita's kids were so cute. I like that moment in the last scene of the movie when Katniss was talking about nightmares with her baby girl. that was cute. That's all I have to say. Good movie. Not perfect but all the actors and actresses did a good job,and in the end everything was alright. 👍👌😂😏😀😏😂👌👍

text: Considering the less than stellar job in the other films, at last in this one they got the mood of the story right. Lawrence channeling her break out role in Winter's Bone carries this film well. Ironically, the stark contrast of the end with the rest of the story is just a bit of a let down. For a clueless, undefined heroine, Catnip only makes the final choices on her own at the very end. A little too late and just like at the end of the second film is sidelined while the events in her world take shape at the end. Prim's fat cat's scene is the only I cried at,  really. In the end the true worst villain of the story turned out to be Coin. I could have liked to see more of Snow's Death, of the aftermath of the events at the Capital. I expected more military action rom the frontlines, not just references to it.

text: while certain plot points were laughably bad, i still found this to be by far the best rip-off of a japanese dystopian story i've seen... well, at least the best 'hunger games' flick.   okay, it's silly and sometimes just stupid, and if there's not some kind of political message the movie-makers/author is trying to get across then they've failed in not avoiding that. i took two things away from the whole thing: 1) egalitarianism is awesome (it's not) and 2) all white leadership is elitist and eve-eel.   so, while the performances were okay overall and i think the production values were very good, the story and characters themselves had a lot of disconnects. there's some illogical bullshit going on here, now! lol. that said, i really did like the aftermath of snow's regime collapse and hawkeye's, er, katnip's arrest ~ it made me wonder just under who's authority was she placed under that arrest. it was an interesting concept.   other than that, though, if you're looking for something that makes sense, well, ya might want to move along unless you're a kid or someone what doesn't watch many movies, lol, because if you watch this objectively it fails in a lot of ways a lot of times.   entertaining? sure, for the most part. a satisfactory ending despite way too many obvious plot points and cliches? yeah, it worked out fairly well, imo. for me i found it to be childishly simplistic, though i liked the authority concept. for the masses who were tricked by nice production values from the very start of the series, i don't see why you wouldn't love this. love it now, because once maturity and experience set in you'll go back years from now and rewatch these things and kinda see just how cheesy and kinda awful a lot of these movies really are.
